if the stock should rally back above 60, the strategist will be making a profit nearly
equal to the original maximum profit that he was aiming for (7 points). Moreover, this
profit is now available anywhere over 60, not just exactly at 60 as it was in the origi-
nal position. Although the chances ofsuch a rally cannot be considered great, it does
not cost the spreader much to restructure himselfinto a position with a much broad-
er maximum profit area.
A similar situation is available ifthe underlying stock moves up in price. In that
case,
the bull spread may be able to be removed at nearly its maximum profit poten-
tial, thereby leaving a bear spread. Again, suppose that the same initial spread was
established but that XYZ has risen to 75. When the underlying stock advances sub-
stantially, the bull spread portion ofthe butterfly spread may expand to near its max-
.
imum potential. Since the strikes are 10 points apart in this bull spread, the widest it
can grow to is 10 points. At the prices shown in Table 10-4, the bull spread — long
July 50 and short July 60 ~ has grown to 9¥2 points. Thus, the bull spread position
could be removed within 1/2 point of its maximum profit potential and the original
butterfly spread would become a bear spread. Note that the closing ofthe bull spread
portion generates a 91/2 point credit: The July 50 is sold at 25'% and the July 60 is
bought back at 16. The original butterfly spread was established at a 3-point debit, so
the net position is the remaining position:

